message.raw:
Write a couple of tests for the stod conversions in parser_urdf.cc

In the first test, we iterate over a map that contains a list
of elements that we want to test for.  For each element, we
parse the XML and then check to make sure that all of the
elements that we expect to be there are actually there.  We
also check that the final number represented is what we expect.
The second test just checks that an invalid number throws a
std::invalid_argument like we expect.

message.raw:
Fix parsing of URDF with an empty origin.

Previously, attempting to parse a URDF file with an empty
origin attribute of xyz or rpy would lead to a crash (attempting
to initialize a std::string with a NULL).  The new code detects
this situation and just adds an origin of 0,0,0,0,0,0 for an
empty origin.  Tests for this are also added.

message.raw:
Fix for compiling with Visual Studio and vcpkg

This commit contains two fixes:

* The first one is to avoid the hardcoding
of the location of the sdformat library (useful to avoid
in multi-configuration CMake generators such as Visual Studio).

* The second one modifies the logic of copying boost dll in the test
directory to support the installation layout of boost when installed
using vcpkg ( https://github.com/Microsoft/vcpkg ). The logic is still
quite hardcoded, but at least now it does not fail to compile if the files
are not found in the assumed location.

message.raw:
Fix signed/unsigned warning in the split function.

The Windows compiler correctly pointed out a signed/unsigned
mismatch in the split function, in that we were storing a negative
number in a size_t (I'm not sure why gcc/clang didn't show this,
but oh well).  Slightly rewrite the split function to not use
negative numbers, which makes things happier.  Note that I also
changed the name of the function here to "split", since I'll be
re-using this function again for other purposes.

message.raw:
Get rid of std::regex in split_double_colon.

As pointed out by scpeters in review, on our oldest
platforms std::regex doesn't work correctly.  Thus, we
use std::basic_string functionality instead, which should
still be O(n).  As a bonus, it is shorter code too!

message.raw:
Significantly simplify Converter::Remove.

In particular, it has no reason to use boost:regex to split
on ::.  It should act a lot more like Add, where it just
takes a specific element or attribute to remove, and does
just that.  As an added bonus, we also add the ability to
remove attributes with this commit.
